{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563685"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:03:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:03:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16848"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16848"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.15,0.14,0.08,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107292"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9538"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16848"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89754"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8970"},{"type":"tags","id":"9042"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22535"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44005"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107292"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with severe bilateral eye pain and photophobia that woke him from sleep. The pain started six hours ago. He works as an apprentice welder and was using an arc welder yesterday afternoon without wearing protective eyewear. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He is unable to open his eyes due to pain. There is bilateral conjunctival injection and lacrimation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Artificial tears and oral analgesia","Topical anaesthetic drops for home use","Bilateral eye patches","Topical antibiotics","Topical steroids"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with ultraviolet keratitis (\u0027arc eye\u0027 or \u0027welder\u0027s flash\u0027), which occurs when the cornea is exposed to excessive ultraviolet radiation during welding without appropriate eye protection. The characteristic delayed onset of symptoms (6-12 hours post-exposure) and bilateral involvement are typical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArtificial tears and oral analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E represent the appropriate supportive management for UV keratitis. Artificial tears help maintain corneal hydration and comfort, while oral analgesics provide pain relief. This condition is self-limiting and typically resolves within 24-48 hours with supportive care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical anaesthetic drops\u003C/strong\u003E may be used briefly in the emergency department for examination purposes, but should never be prescribed for home use as they can cause corneal toxicity, delayed healing, and corneal perforation with repeated use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral eye patches\u003C/strong\u003E are not recommended in modern practice as they do not improve healing, may increase discomfort, and can interfere with normal blinking which aids in corneal recovery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not routinely indicated as UV keratitis is not an infectious condition. They should only be considered if there is evidence of secondary bacterial infection or corneal abrasion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical steroids\u003C/strong\u003E are contraindicated in UV keratitis as they may delay epithelial healing and increase the risk of complications including corneal perforation, particularly if there are corneal defects present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional supportive measures include cool compresses and sunglasses for photophobia. The patient should be advised that symptoms typically resolve within 24-48 hours and to return if symptoms worsen or persist beyond this timeframe. Prevention through appropriate protective equipment is essential for all future welding activities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultraviolet keratitis from welding flash exposure is managed with supportive care including artificial tears and oral analgesia.","Symptoms of arc eye typically develop 6-12 hours after exposure and resolve within 24-48 hours.","Topical anaesthetics should only be used for examination purposes and not prescribed for home use due to risk of corneal damage."],"references":["Bunya VY, Tripathy K, Moon C, Halfpenny C, Rohl A, Patel R. Photokeratitis. EyeWiki. Published January 25, 2025. Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Photokeratitis","McCauley, P. \u0026 Lantos, A. (2017). Management of photokeratitis. Clinical Review in Ophthalmology, 22(2), 112-118.Jacobs DS, Gardiner MF, Givens J. Photokeratitis. UpToDate. Published October 31, 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/photokeratitis"]},"relationships":